title: Update the Definition file of D3.js to v3.5.3
body:
D3.js has been updated to [v3.5 “Mount Sharp”](https://github.com/mbostock/d3/releases/tag/v3.5.0) 2 months ago. There are some new methods in the  latest version. So I try to write the definition of these new methods:
- Add signature of named transitions for concurrent animations on the same element.
- Add signature of d3.layout.pie padAngle, which preserves approximate relative area of arcs.
  (_ps._ I think there maybe something wrong with the definition of `startAngle`,`endAngle` and `padAngle`. Based on the source code of [d3.layout.pie](https://github.com/mbostock/d3/blob/master/src/layout/pie.js#l16#l18), the param `i:number` is needless and should not be pass in. I not quite sure about it. Need more discussion.)
- Add signature of d3.svg.arc cornerRadius for arcs with rounded corners.
- Add signature of d3.behavior.zoom duration for customizing or disabling double-click transitions.
- Add signature of d3.map(array, accessor) for constructing a map by key from an array.
- Add signature of d3.scale.ordinal rangeRoundPoints, a rounded version of rangePoints.
- Add signature of d3.geom.quadtree find for efficient 2D search.
- Add signature of d3.variance and d3.deviation.
- Add signature of d3.shuffle(array, lo, hi) for shuffling a subset of an array.

Besides, I add and fix some signature in the previous version:
- Add the signature of InterpolateZoom
- Add a overload definition of Transition.each(..)
- Add a overload definition of quadtree(Array<number[]>)
- Fix some signature in D3.Base

title: Adding early support for React v0.13.0
body:
React v0.13 is set to come out very soon. This adds early support for React v0.13 by versioning the new files (this should allow installation through TSD without messing up existing functionality). This will allow us to get a headstart on modeling v0.13. This PR is not meant to be a complete modeling but rather to provide a base on which to collaborate and tweak with further PRs.

In particular this PR adds the most significant change which is supporting ES6 classes. ES6 classes (aka "modern") have a slightly different API than classes created through React.createClass (aka "classic"). Also many APIs are deprecated in modern such as `replaceState`, `getDOMNode` and various prop methods.

This also includes slightly modified tests. Most existing functionality seems to work without issue (in other words I don't think the upgrade path is particularly difficult if it's even necessary at all).

**Misc notes**

The existing `Component` interface needed to be changed in order to support extending from the React-provided base class which is called `React.Component`. `Component` now provides the base class implementation. see https://github.com/facebook/react/blob/master/src/modern/class/ReactComponentBase.js and https://github.com/facebook/react/blob/master/src/modern/class/__tests__/ReactES6Class-test.js

The classical implementation is now called `ClassicComponent` and extends `Component` while adding additional API methods. This reflects what happens in reality, see https://github.com/facebook/react/blob/9abd1133c94288c09512f7cf0b8a0b8136df6da7/src/classic/class/ReactClass.js#L787-L791

`CompositeComponent` has been removed since the concept of state is present from the very beginning (ex `React.Component.setState`)

Additional information regarding propTypes and default props: https://github.com/facebook/react/blob/master/src/modern/element/__tests__/ReactJSXElementValidator-test.js

Paging @pspeter3 and @vsiao

title: Add method getItemsAsync and remove nullable in IPromise.done
body:
Hello @basarat , Here are the changes for compatibility with promises of WinJS and WinRT. I've also added a new function.

1.- Add definition method for get folder ítems with range 'getItemsAsync' (the class already contains):
https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/apps/br227287.aspx?cs-save-lang=1&cs-lang=javascript#code-snippet-1

2.- remove nullable in IPromise.done for compatibility with promises of WinJS and WinRT.
currently occurs the following:

example:

``` javascript
var folder: WinJS.IPromise<Windows.Storage.IStorageFolder> = _storageFolder.getFolderAsync("path");
```

the error is: 
**Error 1029**
Can not convert 'Windows.Foundation.IAsyncOperation <Windows.Storage.StorageFolder>' in 'WinJS.IPromise <Windows.Storage.IStorageFolder>':
The property 'done' has been defined as optional in type 'Windows.Foundation.IPromise <T>',
but it is necessary in the type 'WinJS.IPromise <T>'.

WinRT currently contains this promise:

``` JavaScript
export interface IPromise<T> {
   ...
   done? <U>(success?: (value: T) => ...
   ...
}
```

and WinJS

``` JavaScript
export interface IPromise<T> {
   ...
   done<U>(onComplete?: (value: T) => ...
   ...
}
```

so that it is incompatible, to establish compatibility with the promise of WinJS must be removed nullable in done function of promise.

title: fixed typing for async
body:
The improved type system of TS 1.4.x finally failed on some of the definitions.

My main motivation was fixing was `async.parallel`:

```
parallel<T>(tasks: T[], callback?: AsyncResultsCallback<T>): void;
```

It is incorrect. Tasks are functions that callback T as a result. As above TS tries to pass 'task functions' as a result into the master callback which begets profound sorrow.

title: Split modules react and react/addons; exporting Component<P, S, C> class
body:
So... this PR splits `react-0.13.0.d.ts` and `react-addons-0.13.0.d.ts`, with no shared code or interfaces. That feels bad, but there's a good reason why: # The Problem `React.Exports.Component` doesn't have type parameters (it has the type interface `React.ComponentClass`, which is not extendable by a `class`). The reason this seems to work right now is because `React.Component` references the class in the global `React` module, and not in `"react"` or `"react/addons"`. So if you `import react`, `react.Component` is not a class. # The Solution Export `class Component` directly from `module "react"` as well as from `module "react/addons"`. This has some unfortunate side effects: ### Top Level Exports Previously we managed sharing between `"react"` and `"react/addons"` by extending `React.AddonsExports` from `React.Exports`. Now that we need to export a class, we can't use export assignment: ``` ts var exports: React.Exports; export = exports; ``` So every Top Level API method must be exported individually. ``` ts export function createClass(...) export function createElement

(...) export class Component { ... } ``` ### No Shared Interfaces We got away with packing all React-related interfaces into the global `React` module because neither `"react"` nor `"react/addons"` exported any individual elements. Now that they do, If you use ``` ts import React = require("react"); ``` it clobbers the `React` module definition and its interfaces are no longer accessible. This means that we need to either (a) define global interfaces (`ReactElement`, `ReactComponent`, etc.), which is against DT best practices, or (b) declare interfaces in both `"react"` and `"react/addons"` modules. # Attempted Workarounds module merging: ``` ts declare module "react/addons" { import React = require("react"); module React { // <---- (*) var addons: { ... }; } export = React; } ``` _Doesn't work_. The module to be merged `(*)` is ignored completely. # So... This is the conclusion that I came to. We should split up `"react"` and `"react/addons"`, making sure that changes stay in sync between the two files. _Bonus features_: - fixes `static` properties on modern components (needs type annotations) - write better tests for Top-Level API, making sure that they preserve type information (eg. `ClassicComponentClass -> ClassicFactory -> ReactClassicElement -> ClassicComponent`) cc @pspeter3, @jbrantly
